doc.ContractDescription: PLANETARY ROVERS GREATLY EXTEND THE REACH OF HUMAN EXPLORATION. SO FAR THOUGH, THESE ROBOTS HAVE BEEN LONE EXPLORERS, LIMITING HOW BOTH OPERATORS AND THE PUBLIC SEE THEM. IMAGERY OF OUR ROBOTIC ADVENTURERS BOLDLY EXPLORING ANOTHER WORLD IS NOW ONLY POSSIBLE WHEN NEAR THE LANDER OR BY STOPPING TO TAKE A SELFIE. DUE TO THE EXPENSE OF THESE ROVERS, OPERATORS HAVE ALSO USED THEM VERY CAUTIOUSLY, AVOIDING SOME OF THE DESTINATIONS THAT OFFER THE GREATEST SCIENTIFIC PAYOUT BECAUSE THEY ENTAIL RISKS TOO GREAT FOR SUCH AN IMPORTANT ROBOT. GIVEN THE HIGH COSTS OF SENDING ROVERS TO EXTRATERRESTRIAL BODIES, EVEN THE SMALL POSSIBILITY OF LOSING A PRIMARY ROVER PRECLUDES THE EXPLORATION OF THESE IMPORTANT, YET RISKY DESTINATIONS. A PROMISING METHOD OF MITIGATING THE RISKS OF EXPLORING THESE DESTINATIONS IS TO EXPLORE WITH A MULTI ROBOT TEAM SUCH AS A LARGE PRIMARY ROVER ACCOMPANIED BY A SMALLER COMPANION ROVER. IN THIS CONFIGURATION, THE MORE EXPENDABLE AND LESS EXPENSIVE COMPANION ROVER CAN EXPLORE TERRAIN DEEMED TOO HAZARDOUS FOR THE PRIMARY ROVER WITHOUT RISKING THE MISSION IF LOST. THE BENEFITS OF THIS SYMBIOTIC ARCHITECTURE EXTEND FAR BEYOND RISK REDUCTION. SYMBIOTIC ROVERS WILL EXPLORE GREATER AREA MORE EFFICIENTLY THAN IS POSSIBLE WITH A SINGLE ROVER. COMPANION ROVERS COULD PRESENT OPERATORS WITH SEPARATE VIEWPOINTS, NOT ONLY OF OBJECTS OF INTEREST, BUT OF THE ROVERS THEMSELVES. PAIRED ROVERS WILL SERVE AS MOBILE CAMERA CREWS FOR EACH OTHER, TAKING STUNNING IMAGERY AND VIDEO OF ROVERS EXPLORING OTHER WORLDS. SUCH VIEWS WILL NOT ONLY ASSIST OPERATORS IN DETERMINING THE BEST WAY TO APPROACH AN OBJECT, OR HOW TO MANEUVER A ROVER IF STUCK BUT ALSO TRANSFORM HOW THE PUBLIC VIEWS ROBOTIC PLANETARY EXPLORERS.

EXAMINING AIRCRAFT, SATELLITE, AND MODELING DATA FROM HS3 TO ADVANCE UNDERSTANDING OF HURRICANES ACCURATE FORECASTS OF TROPICAL CYCLONES ARE NEEDED TO MITIGATE THE POTENTIALLY LARGE ECONOMIC AND HUMAN IMPACT UPON LANDFALL. YET, FORECASTING TROPICAL CYCLONE SIZE AND INTENSITY REMAINS A DIFFICULT TASK LARGELY BECAUSE OF OUR LACK OF OBSERVATIONS AND UNDERSTANDING OF A STORMS INTERNAL DYNAMICS. THIS PROPOSAL WILL FOCUS ON UTILIZING AIRBORNE RADAR DATA, SATELLITE OBSERVATIONS, AND MODEL SIMULATIONS IN AN EFFORT TO ADVANCE THE KNOWLEDGE AND PREDICTION OF TROPICAL CYCLONES (NASAS WEATHER FOCUS AREA). DURING THE NASA HS3 FIELD CAMPAIGN (2012-2014), THE NASA HIWRAP RADAR WAS DEPLOYED INTO HURRICANE GONZALO (2014) TO DOCUMENT THE REFLECTIVITY AND KINEMATIC STRUCTURES OF ITS INTERNAL FEATURES. HIWRAP IS A RECENTLY DEVELOPED RADAR WITH A UNIQUE SCANNING GEOMETRY, WHICH REQUIRES NEW DATA PROCESSING ALGORITHMS. THE PROPOSED WORK WILL DEVELOP AND EXAMINE PROCESSING ALGORITHMS AND APPLY THEM TO THE HS3 HIWRAP DATA. HIWRAP AND OTHER AIRBORNE INSTRUMENTS WILL PROVIDE HIGH-RESOLUTION OBSERVATIONS OF THE INTERNAL FEATURES, WHILE SATELLITE OBSERVATIONS WILL PROVIDE NECESSARY TEMPORAL AND SPATIAL CONTEXT TO SUPPLEMENT THE ANALYSIS. THESE DATA WILL BE COMBINED TO ASSESS THE CHARACTERISTICS OF THE OBSERVED FEATURES AND TO INTERPRET GONZALOS DYNAMICAL EVOLUTION. WE WILL ALSO DEVELOP A KNOWLEDGE BASE FOR SATELLITE REPRESENTATIONS OF AIRCRAFT-OBSERVED INTERNAL PROCESSES THAT CAN BE USED TO ASSESS AND PREDICT TROPICAL CYCLONE EVOLUTION WORLDWIDE. LASTLY, MODEL SIMULATIONS WITH DATA ASSIMILATION WILL BE EXAMINED TO LINK THE PROCESSES INVOLVED IN GONZALOS EVOLUTION. WE WILL USE MODEL SENSITIVITY TESTING AND FULLY ASSIMILATED MODEL ANALYSES TO DETERMINE THE CRITICAL FACTORS GOVERNING TROPICAL CYCLONE INTENSITY AND SIZE. THESE SAME RESEARCH STEPS WILL BE USED TO ANALYZE FUTURE HIWRAP OBSERVATIONS OF TROPICAL CYCLONES, WHICH WILL BE COLLECTED DURING NOAAS SENSING HAZARDS WITH OPERATIONAL UNMANNED TECHNOLOGY (SHOUT) FIELD PROGRAM. WITH THESE RESULTS, WE WILL HELP TO IMPROVE HURRICANE FORECASTING, WHICH IS A KEY GOAL OF NASAS EARTH SCIENCE RESEARCH PROGRAM.
